gemini_pro.summary:
The Knowledge Graph is highly accurate and aligned with the PDF source of truth. All critical data points including dimensions, airflows, weights, cartridge counts, and housing lengths for the main product families (GDP, GDB, GDC, GDMI, and their Flex variants) match the PDF tables exactly. The graph correctly identifies the discrepancy in the PDF regarding GDMI lengths and adheres to the correct table values.

The only findings are minor discrepancies in material availability for accessory products (PT, TT, and Filter Profil). While the PDF tables for these specific items list 'FZ' as the standard, the page headers and text indicate that other materials (AZ, RF, SF, ZM) are available on request or as options, which the graph does not currently reflect for TT and Filter Profil, and partially misses for PT.

findings.description: Graph allows material AZ for GDMI FLEX, but the PDF shows GDMI FLEX material icons only for FZ and ZM (no AZ).
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX page shows material icons: FZ, AZ, ZM? (actual GDMI FLEX page shows only FZ and ZM icons at top-left; no RF/SF and no clear AZ availability stated in text; text: "GDMI FLEX tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ej i rostfritt.")
findings.recommendation: Remove AZ from GDMI FLEX available materials unless you have a separate confirmed source. Set available materials to {ZM (default), FZ} per catalog.

findings.description: Graph restricts GDMI materials to AZ and ZM only, but PDF text explicitly says GDMI can be made in ZM and also in stainless (rostfritt).
findings.pdf_says: GDMI section text: "GDMI tillverkas vanligen i ZM. ... i Rostfritt." (and header icons show AZ and ZM, but text adds stainless capability).
findings.recommendation: Add RF (and/or SF if offered) as available material for GDMI, or model stainless as a special-order material with proper constraints/lead time.

findings.description: Family-level corrosion class in graph is C2, but material-level mapping implies FZ is C3; PDF states GDP is usually galvanized and corrosion class C2 (product execution), while material page states FZ sheet is C3. Graph currently mixes these without an explicit rule/hierarchy, which can cause wrong environmental recommendations.
findings.pdf_says: GDP text: "GDP tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat. Korrosivitets klass C2." Material page: "FZ ... Z275, korrosivitets klass C3."
findings.graph_says: GDP corrosion class: C2; Material FZ corrosion class: C3
findings.recommendation: Define precedence: store 'product execution corrosion class' separately from 'raw material corrosion class', or align GDP corrosion class logic to material+construction. Avoid contradictory single field.

findings.description: Same corrosion-class ambiguity as GDP: product says C2 while FZ material is C3 in material table; graph sets family C2 and material FZ C3.

findings.recommendation: Same as finding #3: separate fields or a rule-based derivation to prevent contradictory corrosion guidance.

findings.graph_says: GDC corrosion class: C2; FZ material: C3

The discrepancy is in labeling: graph 'Weight Long (kg)' name includes '750', but the family uses 750/800; also weight mapping for 1800x900 is unusually low for short vs comparable sizes and should be double-validated.

openai.summary: Most numeric tables (sizes, airflows, weights, cartridge counts) in the graph match the catalog very closely for GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX and GDMI FLEX. I did not find row-level numeric mismatches in the provided dimension/airflow/weight tables versus the PDF tables for these families; the graph appears to have captured essentially all listed rows (including the large GDMI matrix up to 2400x2400). The main data-integrity risks are not in the numbers but in metadata modeling: material availability is over-permissive compared to what is explicitly confirmed per family, and corrosion-class data is internally contradictory because the PDF gives both a product execution corrosion class (often C2) and material corrosion classes (e.g., FZ=C3).
openai.summary_continued: The most actionable corrections are: (1) fix GDMI FLEX materials (remove AZ unless confirmed); (2) add stainless availability to GDMI (per text) or explicitly model it as special-order; (3) resolve corrosion-class precedence by separating product-level vs material-level ratings; and (4) correct construction/service-access metadata for PFF and GDMI FLEX. Finally, standardize code-format normalization (EXL and Filter profil) to prevent downstream parsing/configuration errors.

anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates good overall coverage of the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC filter housing catalog. All 12 product families from the PDF are represented, and the vast majority of dimensional data, weights, airflow ratings, and cartridge counts are accurately captured. The graph correctly models the material availability for each family, including the important restriction that GDMI and GDMI FLEX are not available in stainless steel (RF/SF).

The most significant issues found are: (1) A potential data error in the GDB 1800x900 short weight (36 kg in both PDF and graph, but physically implausible given that 1800x600 weighs 47 kg), (2) Some filter module breakdown discrepancies for GDB sizes where ¼ and ½ module counts appear swapped (e.g., 600x900 and 1200x900), and (3) The GDMI default material question (graph says ZM default, but PDF example code shows AZ). The GDC FLEX dimension table in the PDF has a notable width/height swap that should be documented.

Minor gaps include missing metadata for hinge types, door insulation details, maximum filter classes (F9), and the aluminum framework construction detail for GDMI/GDMI FLEX. The PFF construction type is marked as 'BOLTED (PENDING_MIKAEL)' which needs resolution. Overall, the graph is approximately 72% complete and accurate, with the core product data being reliable but some edge cases and metadata enrichment opportunities remaining.

openai.final_assessment: Key consensus items: the GDMI length discrepancy is real in the PDF (text vs dimension table), and the graph following the dimension table (600/650 and 850/900) is reasonable. Several accessory-material findings from other evaluators should be reframed: PT/TT/Filter Profil list FZ as standard while other materials are only 'på begäran', so the graph should not treat these as missing standard materials unless it supports a 'special order' availability attribute. The strongest correction from peer review is that my own finding about GDMI needing stainless material availability is not supported cleanly by this catalog; the GDMI section appears internally inconsistent and should be flagged rather than asserted. My original critical issue about GDMI FLEX incorrectly allowing AZ remains: the GDMI FLEX page shows only FZ and ZM and the example code uses FZ. Overall, the graph appears broadly accurate on core dimensional/selection data but needs better modeling for (a) standard vs on-request material availability and (b) resolving/annotating catalog inconsistencies (default material and corrosion-class semantics).

anthropic_opus.final_assessment: After peer review, the knowledge graph is moderately accurate but has several important issues that need resolution. The most critical findings confirmed across evaluators are: (1) GDMI default material discrepancy between text (ZM) and example code (AZ) on page 11; (2) Corrosion class ambiguity where product families show C2 but the underlying FZ material is rated C3 - this needs a clear data model hierarchy; (3) GDB 1800x900 weight data appears to be a PDF source error (36 kg is physically impossible); (4) GDMI length description text contradicts the dimension table (text says 550/600 and 800/850, table says 600/650 and 850/900); (5) Several module breakdown errors in GDB (e.g., 600x900 and 1200x900); (6) Material availability for accessories (TT, Filter Profil) is incomplete in the graph. OpenAI's claim that GDMI supports stainless steel is definitively wrong - the PDF explicitly excludes it. OpenAI's claim that GDMI FLEX lacks AZ is also incorrect per the page 18 icons. Gemini's overall score of 95 is too generous given the corrosion class modeling issues and module breakdown errors. The graph needs targeted corrections but the core dimensional data, flow rates, and product structure are largely sound.

findings.description: BFF 'Passar filter' dimensions (e.g., 305x305 → 287x287, 610x610 → 592x592) from the PDF table are not stored in the graph's BFF dimension modules, limiting filter matching capability.

findings.description: GDB, GDC, and GDC FLEX all have double-walled insulated service doors as standard, despite the cabinet body being single-wall uninsulated. The graph correctly marks construction as SINGLE_WALL_UNINSULATED but does not capture the insulated door detail, which is a key specification point.

findings.graph_says: Construction: SINGLE_WALL_UNINSULATED, no door insulation detail
findings.recommendation: Add a 'door_insulation' attribute to capture that the service door is double-walled and heat/condensation insulated for GDB, GDC, and GDC FLEX families.

findings.description: Different product families use different hinge and lock types that are not captured in the graph: GDP uses piano hinges (pianogångjärn) with JHL lock; GDB/GDC/GDC FLEX use pin hinges (sprintgångjärn) with JHL lock; GDMI/GDMI FLEX use adjustable hinges (justerbara gångjärn) with door lock (dörrlucklås).

findings.recommendation: Add hinge_type and lock_type attributes to each product family for specification completeness.

findings.description: GDMI FLEX weight table on page 18 has both column headers labeled 'Vikt kg 1100/1150' (a PDF typo). The first column should be 'Vikt kg 850/900' based on the data pattern. The graph correctly interprets the first column as 850/900 weights and the second as 1100/1150 weights.

final_report.summary:
The MANN+HUMMEL HVAC filter housing knowledge graph demonstrates strong accuracy in its core dimensional data, including sizes, weights, airflow ratings, and cartridge counts across all 12 product families (GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX, BFF, PFF, PT, TT, EXL, Filter Profil). The vast majority of numeric table data has been faithfully transcribed from the PDF catalog, and the graph correctly covers all listed size variants including the extended GDMI range up to 2400x2400. The graph appropriately follows dimension table values over descriptive text where the PDF contains internal inconsistencies (e.g., GDMI lengths).

The most significant issues are structural/metadata in nature rather than numeric errors. The corrosion class data model creates contradictions by storing both product-level ratings (C2 for FZ-based cabinets) and material-level ratings (C3 for FZ sheet) without a clear hierarchy. The GDMI default material has a genuine PDF inconsistency between text (ZM) and example code (AZ) that needs product team resolution. The PFF construction type and GDMI FLEX service access type contain incorrect metadata values. One suspected PDF source error exists in the GDB 1800x900 short weight (36 kg, physically implausible). Material availability for accessory products (TT, Filter Profil) is incomplete, missing on-request options shown by page icons.

Overall, the graph is reliable for product selection and configuration purposes, with the core engineering data being accurate. The recommended corrections focus on metadata modeling improvements (corrosion class hierarchy, construction details, material availability flags) rather than fundamental data errors. With the identified corrections applied, the graph would achieve a high level of catalog fidelity suitable for production use.
